'''UCL Partners''' is an [[academic health science centre]] located in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is the largest academic health science centre in the world, treats more than 1.5 million patients each year, has a combined annual turnover of around £2 billion and includes around 3,500 [[scientists]], senior researchers and consultants.<ref>{{Cite news | publisher = The Guardian | title = NHS hospitals to forge £2bn research link-up with university | accessdate =6 September 2010| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2008/aug/07/health.highereducation | date=7 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | publisher = BBC News | title = Major health research group forms | accessdate =6 September 2010| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/7547034.stm | date =7 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | publisher =London Evening Standard | title = Health giants join forces in research powerhouse | accessdate =6 September 2010| url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23528367-details/Health+giants+join+forces+in+research+powerhouse/article.do | date =7 August 2008 }}</ref>

The members of UCL Partners are: [[Barts Health NHS Trust]], [[Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Trust]], [[Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]], [[Queen Mary, University of London]], [[Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust]], [[University College London]] (UCL) and [[University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref name=aboutus>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclpartners.com/about-us|title=About Us|accessdate=6 September 2010|publisher=UCL Partners}}</ref> 

==History==
[[Image:Finsbury moorfields eye hospital 1.jpg|200px|right|thumb|[[Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust|Moorfields Eye Hospital]]]]
In July 2007 the then Health Minister Lord Darzi recommended the establishment of a number of academic health science centres in the UK.<ref name=natbio1>{{Cite journal| author = Nuala Moran | year = 2008 | month = | title = London forges £2 billion research cluster | journal = Nature Biotechnology | volume = 26 | issue =  | pages =1056 | id = | doi = 10.1038/nbt1008-1056 | url = http://www.nature.com/nbt/journal/v26/n10/full/nbt1008-1056.html}}</ref> 

Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Trust, Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, Royal Free Hampstead NHS Trust (now Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust), UCL and University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust announced their intention to form UCL Partners in August 2008.<ref name=aboutus/><ref name=natbio1/> In February 2009 Professor Sir Cyril Chantler was appointed as the first Chair of UCL Partners and it was officially designated as one of the UK’s first academic health science centres by the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|UK Department of Health]] in March 2009.<ref name=aboutus/> 

Key strategic appointments were made in summer 2009, including Professor David Fish as Managing Director and seven Programme Directors. An alliance between UCL, UCL Partners, [[Yale University]] and [[Yale-New Haven Hospital]] was announced in October 2009.<ref name=yaleucl>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclpartners.com/yale-ucl|title=Yale-UCL Collaboration|accessdate=6 September 2010|publisher=UCL Partners}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The UCL Partners academic strategy and key research priorities were agreed in November 2009.<ref name=aboutus/> In October 2011 it was reported that [[Barts and The London NHS Trust]] and [[Queen Mary, University of London]] had agreed to join UCL Partners, making it the largest academic health science centre in the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://m.hsj.co.uk/5036604.article|title=UCL Partners to become 'biggest AHSC in the world'|accessdate=30 October 2011|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=17 October 2011}}</ref>

[[Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Hospitals NHS Trust]] agreed to join UCL Partners in April 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/hsj-local/acute-trusts/barking-havering-and-redbridge-university-hospitals-nhs-trust/london-acute-joins-ucl-partners-academic-health-science-centre/5043842.article|title=London acute joins UCL Partners academic health science centre|accessdate=18 May 2012|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>

==Organisation==
The governing body of UCL Partners is UCL Partners Ltd, a company limited by guaranteed. The governance arrangements consist of:<ref name=aboutus/> 

* A board led by an independent chair (currently Sir Cyril Chantler).
* An executive group comprising the four chief executives of the four NHS Trusts, the UCL Vice-Provost (health), the UCL Research Dean and the Managing Director of UCL Partners.
* Internationally-renowned clinical academics to direct programmes for research, service delivery and education.

==Research==
[[Image:Great Ormond Street Hospital.jpg|200px|right|thumb|[[Great Ormond Street Hospital]]]]

According to the independent Thomson ISI Essential Science Indicators, which assesses organisations according to the number of highly-cited publications produced, UCL Partners is ranked: first in the world for research into [[ophthalmology]]; second in the world (and first in Europe) for [[neuroscience]]; first in Europe for [[clinical medicine]]; and second in Europe for [[immunology]].<ref name=aboutus/>

UCL Partners’ research priorities are divided into eleven key programme areas:<ref name=aboutus/>

*[[Infectious disease|Infectious Diseases]]
*[[Neurological]] Disorders
*[[Ophthalmology|Eyes and Vision]]
*[[Cardiovascular]] Health
*[[Paediatrics|Children’s Health]]
*[[Women's health|Women’s Health]]
*[[Immunology]] and [[Organ transplantation|Transplantation]]
*[[Cancer]]
*[[Mental Health]]
*[[Dental disease|Oral Health]]
*[[Otolaryngology|Ear, nose and throat]]

